%I A179579 #49 Jul 22 2026 07:56:49
%S A179579 37,73,142,276,539,1059,2092,4150,8257,16461,32858,65640,131191,
%T A179579 262279,524440,1048746,2097341,4194513,8388838,16777468,33554707,
%U A179579 67109163,134218052,268435806,536871289,1073742229,2147484082,4294967760,8589935087,17179869711,34359738928
%N A179579 Number of permutations of {1, ..., n+4} with p(i) < i at least n times more often than p(i) > i.
%C A179579 The recurrence would also extend to an a(0) if the definition were made to exclude the identity permutation.
%C A179579 I have proved the formulas which were only "empirical" up to today, cf. link. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 16 2026
%C A179579 Also the sum of the rightmost 3 values in the rows of A062866 (starting at row 5 there). - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 16 2026
%H A179579 R. H. Hardin, <a href="/A179579/b179579.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n=1..100</a>
%H A179579 M. F. Hasler and R. J. Mathar, <a href="/A179582/a179582_3.pdf">Hardin's exceedance excesses A179579-A179582</a>, July 2026.
%H A179579 <a href="/index/Rec#order_04">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (5,-9,7,-2).
%F A179579 a(n) = 5*a(n-1)-9*a(n-2)+7*a(n-3)-2*a(n-4).
%F A179579 G.f.: -x*(-37+112*x-110*x^2+36*x^3) / ( (2*x-1)*(x-1)^3 ). - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 19 2010 (via SeqFan Mailing List)
%F A179579 a(n) = (n+4)*(n+1)/2 + 2^(n+4). - _R. J. Mathar_, May 26 2016
%F A179579 a(n) = A179571(n) + n+1. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 16 2026
%e A179579 From _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 15 2026: (Start)
%e A179579 For n = 1, the following a(1) = 37 permutations of 1..5 satisfy the condition, where we have written in (.) the excess of "p(i) < i" over "p(i) > i":
%e A179579   [1,2,5,3,4] (1), [1,4,2,3,5] (1), [1,5,2,3,4] (2), [1,5,2,4,3] (1), [1,5,3,2,4] (1),
%e A179579   [2,1,5,3,4] (1), [2,5,1,3,4] (1),
%e A179579   [3,1,2,4,5] (1), [3,1,2,5,4] (1), [3,1,5,2,4] (1), [3,5,1,2,4] (1), [3,5,2,1,4] (1),
%e A179579   [4,1,2,3,5] (2), [4,1,2,5,3] (1), [4,1,3,2,5] (1), [4,1,5,2,3] (1), [4,1,5,3,2] (1),
%e A179579   [4,2,1,3,5] (1), [4,5,1,2,3] (1), [4,5,1,3,2] (1), [4,5,2,1,3] (1), [4,5,2,3,1] (1),
%e A179579   [5,1,2,3,4] (3), [5,1,2,4,3] (2), [5,1,3,2,4] (2), [5,1,3,4,2] (1), [5,1,4,2,3] (1),
%e A179579   [5,1,4,3,2] (1), [5,2,1,3,4] (2), [5,2,1,4,3] (1), [5,2,3,1,4] (1), [5,3,1,2,4] (1),
%e A179579   [5,3,2,1,4] (1), [5,4,1,2,3] (1), [5,4,1,3,2] (1), [5,4,2,1,3] (1), [5,4,2,3,1] (1).
%e A179579 For example, consider the permutation
%e A179579   p = (p(i), i=1..5) = (2, 1, 5, 3, 4)
%e A179579                     i:  1  2  3  4  5
%e A179579             p(i) vs i:  >  <  >  <  <  =>  Excess of '<': 3 - 2 = 1 >= n = 1.
%e A179579 We have 3 times '<' and 2 times '>', so there is n = 1 more '<' than '>'.
%e A179579 The only permutation that has an excess of 3 '<'s is obviously [5,1,2,3,4]. (End)
%o A179579 (PARI) A179579(n)=(n+1)*(n+=4)\2+2^n
%o A179579 A179579(n, show=0)={my(cnt=0); forperm(n+4, p, sum(i=1,#p, (p[i]<i)-(p[i]>i)) >= n && cnt++ && show && printf("%d, ",Vec(p))); cnt} \\ For illustration. - _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 15 2026
%o A179579 (Python) A179579=lambda n: (n+1)*(n+4)//2+2**(n+4) # _M. F. Hasler_, Jul 16 2026
%Y A179579 Cf. A179580 ([n+5]) - A179586 ([n+11]) for similar statistics, A179571 - A179578 (similar with excess exactly n), A179566 - A179570 (fixed minimum excess), A179564 - A179565 (fixed exact excess).
%K A179579 nonn,easy,changed
%O A179579 1,1
%A A179579 _R. H. Hardin_
